<br>
I guess I could be called a casual gamer, although I have spent whole weekends playing.  I have a job and can only play a couple hours at night if that.  Lately I have been working Saturdays too.<br>
<br>
The player base of any server is a creature that from the exact moment of creation of a server, becomes a critical mass gaining momentum, day after day, until eventually all fairly regular players have a level 60.  What is Verant going to do about this?  Probably nothing.  What can they do?  More expansions?  With SWOG coming out within the next two years, I am sure their priority is not to keep this game running full steam.<br>
<br>
I see someone say they are going to do something about twinking.  What can they do about that?  All it does is punish everyone who doesn’t already have a level 50 or so character and who has not had a chance to farm like the rest. Most people have twinked the hell out of their alts now if they have a level 50 character.  It is not uncommon to see a level 6 character in gear that should be for level 45 and above.<br>
<br>
Bjarki<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ullorianlanys.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Llorian Lanys</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Boardaholic</span><br> <font color=#000033>(2/4/02 8:03:29 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/feqasylumrantsandravesbalancingissues.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1641.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.mindspring.com/~suretang/images/usf2.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Death of EQ's Casual-Raid Playerbase</span><hr size=1> Thats an extremely well written post.<br>
<br>
I think randomizing the spawn times would cut down on the uberguild competition somewhat, but wouldnt do a thing for the more casual players.<br>
<br>
The problem is, on the day of the patch, the uberguilds run around with &quot;priorities&quot; of what to do first, based on the loot they want to get (or the loot they dont want their &quot;competition&quot; to get).<br>
<br>
After a day or 2, they are basically sitting on their butts, because everything is dead.<br>
<br>
If you randomize the loot, you space it out more, sure, but the uber guilds will generally have more people online than casual guilds ( even casual guilds with power ...), and will tend to mobilize faster than casual guilds.  <br>
<br>
Spacing it out, means that the uber guilds have a shot at killing EVERYTHING.  Leaving it the way it is, means that they cant be in more than one place at the same time, so around patch day usually SOMETHING is available.<br>
<br>
I wish i had an answer for it, but i dont.  It sort of becomes a ' when in rome, do as the romans do&quot;type of thing.  Unfortunately, unless the server set up some sort of rotation ( which , due to the style of players we have here, i dont see happening ), even casual guilds have to &quot;play like the big boys&quot;, if they want to do anything.<br>
<br>
I agree with the original poster quite a bit, but dont have any ideas of how to fix it with the current game engine.<br>
