The player that was out to make friends, adventure, and <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> not</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> advance his character's power in terms of what he could achieve was always dead in this game.  To me this is the casual player. Others of us are just time challenged  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ushallandra.showPublicProfile?language=EN>shallandra</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>h0x0r!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(2/4/02 9:23:02 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/feqasylumrantsandravesbalancingissues.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1641.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Death of EQ's Casual-Raid Playerbase</span><hr size=1> True: Casual gamers pay $10 a month.  But so does everyone else.  It is not fair to those people who have plans, to suspend them for hours if not indefinately simply because some people have RL commitments.  EQ is a game.  People are paying to have fun.  Its hardly fun to just sit around and twiddle your thumbs.  If a mob pops and you and your friends have the power to take it down, there is no reason why you shouldn't.  Thats what your paying for.  Just like everyone else.  For the people who have RL commitments... sorry, sucks to be you, but that is your problem and shouldn't entrap everyone else to be limited to your schedules.<br>
