<br>
One thing that is for certain, as the server gets  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ukaledan.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kaledan</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>p0\/\/3r-p0sT3r!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(2/4/02 9:45:39 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/feqasylumrantsandravesbalancingissues.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1641.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Death of EQ's Casual-Raid Playerbase</span><hr size=1> Here's how I would handle this, if I were god of EQ:<br>
<br>
50,000 to 5,000,000 pp buys you a guild hall, in a special zone created for the purpose. This would have entry restricted by guild (e.g. a teleporter that won't work unless you have the right guild tag).<br>
<br>
In the guid hall there would be some special NPCs, such as guild bankers, guild-only merchants, and, the key thing, guild-only quest NPCs.<br>
<br>
Some of those NPCs would effectively be triggers for epic encounters:<br>
<br>
/say 'I want to visit the Plane of Spicy Food'<br>
/say 'I challenge Rogan Josh'<br>
<br>
Some of these would work at any time, the best risk/reward ones would be triggerrable once a week or less. For the affected zones, you simply couldn't enter if another guild was already there.<br>
<br>
Buying a better guild hall would get you some extra NPCs. Others would require quests to activate ('I will gather the components you need to cast the summoning spell'). <br>
<br>
